<font color="#FF0000">A FEW COMMENTS</font><br>
<tt>Sat Apr 19 20:38:02 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Tom,<br><br>
I agree with you about e-mail, and I too consider it a privileged and private communication, unless it is with a &quot;public&quot; personality whose words by their deliberate choice have impact on a large audience. In contrast, you and I are private individuals and have a mutual understanding of trust and respect for each other. Those with web sites whose foundations rest upon their words and the words of others in a borderline commercial arena with books to sell or offer and discussion groups are not so &quot;private&quot; unless they indicate their comments are &quot;off the record&quot;. I see Doc Spatz's correspondence with KT more in the line as the conduct of a reporter. The problem with the web is that everything is written. There have been times when I have been interviewed by reporters and I have *verbally* &quot;gone off the record&quot; with private information to help their understanding and appreciation, and I was respected for that and confidentially was preserved, but I have no illusions that what I said on the record was fair game for all to see.<br>
The web is not so forgiving.<br><br>
Such is the ethic of the press. I feel Doc acted within this intent, so I am not too concerned about KT.<br><br>
Doc, <br><br>
In no way did I have any thought at any time that your interactions in this KT arena were manipulative.<br><br>
On another subject:<br><br>
While I was in New Haven, CT, at Yale, last night, I saw a great program on their local cable called &quot;Free Speech TV&quot;. It featured a short documentary called &quot;Their Own Vietnam&quot; and was based upon interviews with US Service Women NamVets. It really tore me up. Their feelings were emotionally very close to those that reside in my head. I really connected. I will try to track this down and get a copy, and pass it around. Everyone really needs to see this. I haven't given much thought to the women who were there with us, until now. My thoughts are with them, too.<br><br>
  
<p><code>-- art16@ix.netcom.com  (Arthur Varanelli) </code><p>


